title: 31 Days of Andi Mack - Day 8
body:
Whoops! I have fallen off the wagon a bit, and have not been posted on the proper day due to work and technical difficulties. Playing catch up, so apologies.

Who had the best character development?

Until the series is (hopefully) complete with a satisfying ending, I cannot give a proper answer to this question. Right now, there are storylines and developments that I am not happy with, but the final product might make it all worth it, Until then, here are the developments I like the most right now.

CeCe Mack

CeCe started out a very strict parent who really tried to shelter Andi from everything in the world since she felt that she failed in doing so with Bex. Her and Bex’s relationship was very strained and became even more strained when Bex told Andi the truth. However, she has learned to loosen up and communicate her love/pride for both Andi and Bex, who definitely needed to hear those things from her mother. She truly accepts her role as a grandmother now.

TJ Kippen

With the exception of THAT scene (see day 4), TJ’s development has been really well-handled. When he showed up at the swing set and let his guard down in front of Cyrus, that was the true turning point of his character. They introduced him as a bully (maybe leaned a little too hard on the “sexist” button when doing so), introduced his math problems three episodes into his arc, and showed his softer side four. They also gave him a realistic arc. He and Buffy do not magically get along simply because she knows about his learning disability, or because he is friends with Cyrus. They still hate each other until much later. And that is human nature.
